ce:section.ce:para:
We first determined the minimal inhibitory concentration (MIC) by a standard dilution method at which >99% of the isolates were inhibited. We tested four bacterial strains, including Gram-negative (E. coli and P. aeruginosa) and Gram-positive (S. aureus and S. epidermidis) bacteria, for evaluation of the antibacterial activity of our X/N−PGQDs without and with light irradiation. Fig. 3
                        A shows the colony formation assays of E. coli and S. aureus in the absence and presence of spermidine, the mixture of HCl and spermidine (0.005 μg mL−1; the molar ratio of HCl-to-spermidine is 3) or Cl/N−PGQDs-270 (i.e., Cl/N−PGQDs synthesized at 270 °C; 0.005 μg mL−1); see also Fig. S7 (Supporting Information) for S. epidermidis and P. aeruginosa. The Cl/N−PGQDs-270 treated group, exposed to white LED light irradiation (350 W m−2) for just 1 min, shows >99% inhibition of the bacteria. The MIC values for the Cl/N−PGQDs-270 with LED light irradiation are 0.005 and 0.05 μg mL−1 for E. coli and S. aureus, respectively, which are nearly 100-fold lower than those without light exposure (0.45 and 4.95 μg mL−1) (Fig. 3B and Table 1
                        ). The other X/N−PGQDs also show similar behavior upon light-irradiation, whereby the light strongly boosts their antibacterial activity (>100-fold improvement). In comparison with the Cl/N−PGQDs groups, the mixtures of HX and spermidine (MIC>100 μg mL−1; in terms of spermidine) exhibit negligible antibacterial activity toward the representative bacteria, even with LED light irradiation. We also noted that the MIC values of the Cl/N−PGQDs-270 without (ca. 0.5 μg mL−1) and with (ca. 0.005 μg mL−1) light irradiation toward E. coli are much lower than that of ∼5 nm carbon dots prepared from spermidine (ca. 2–4 μg mL−1), and also that of Cl-doped GQDs (50 μg mL−1) exposed to simulated sunlight (1000 W m−2) for 2 h [20,32]. Cl/N−PGQDs-270 also shows a superior photodynamic inactivation at just 1 min irradiation when compared to amine-functionalized CQDs with highly positive charges (ζ∼+44 mV) which require 1 mg mL−1 with an illumination time of 60 min [71]. The photobactericidal activity of Cl/N−PGQDs-270, based on the MIC value, is also much lower (>100-fold) than most reported metal and metal oxide nanoparticles, which usually require irradiation of intense light (>1000 W m−2) over a long period (>10 min) [72].
